My starting point for the earlier research I did with Selim was how to addr=
ess exploitation among domestic workers in the UK to encourage policy develo=
pment in this area (e.g. the removal of tied visa). I hope (still) that we c=
an generate an prevalence estimator to focus policy attention on the scale o=
f exploitation. So, I was coming at this from a real world problem, rather t=
han selecting a setting to accommodate the use of a method or set of methods=
.=20

You do ask for my opinion specifically on the use of hybrid methods for acc=
essing hard to reach populations such as domestic workers. I would advocate =
this. Findings from our earlier study  suggest that, in the UK at least, dom=
estic worker's networks are unusually sparse when compared to those of other=
 groups for whom RDS methods have been used (for example: intravenous drug u=
sers). We managed to reach nearly 100 domestic workers using RDS and, in so =
doing, were then able to gather scale-up data  - although in hindsight we co=
uld have asked those identified as members of the hidden population a furthe=
r set of questions to also enable G-NSUM calculations to be performed - foll=
owing NORC's suggested approach I would therefore advocate a raft of composi=
